==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Scuff
<hw>Scuff</hw> <pr>(sk⟦ucr⟧f)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. D.
<ets>schoft</ets> shoulder, Goth. <ets>skuft</ets> hair of the head. Cf.
<er>Scruff</er>.]</ety> <def>The back part of the neck; the
scruff.</def> <mark>[Prov. Eng.]</mark> <rj><au>Ld.
Lytton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Scuff</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Scuff
<hw>Scuff</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Scuffed</conjf> <pr>(sk⟦ucr⟧ft)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Scuffing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[See <er>Scuffle</er>.]</ety>
<def>To walk without lifting the feet; to proceed with a scraping or
dragging movement; to shuffle.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Scuff</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Scuff
<hw>Scuff</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Scuffed</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Scuffing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To cause a blemish
on the surface of, by scraping against an object; <as>as, he
<ex>scuffed</ex> his shoe on the ground</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To scrape with one's foot; <as>as, he
<ex>scuffed</ex> the chair leg with his shoe</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Scuffle</ent>⟦br⟧
